Aggregation

Agregation is reducing the column(s) to individual number.

In[2]:
from IPython.display import Image
display(Image(filename='./samples_rw/aggregation.png', width=500))

Transformation

Transformation gives the same column numbers in the result as the numbers from the column.

We transforms the column to new columns values with the same number of items from the column.

In[3]:
from IPython.display import Image
display(Image(filename='./samples_rw/transformation.png', width=500))

https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/user_guide/groupby.html#aggregation

Pandas aggregation functions: Method

Description

any ( )

Compute whether any of the values in the groups are truthy

all ( )

Compute whether all of the values in the groups are truthy

count( )

Compute the number of non-NA values in the groups

cov() *

Compute the covariance of the groups

first()

Compute the first occurring value in each group

idxmax()

Compute the index of the maximum value in each group

idxmin()

Compute the index of the minimum value in each group

last()

Compute the last occurring value in each group

max()

Compute the maximum value in each group

mean()

Compute the mean of each group

median()

Compute the median of each group

min()

Compute the minimum value in each group

nunique()

Compute the number of unique values in each group

prod()

Compute the product of the values in each group

quantile()

Compute a given quantile of the values in each group

sem()

Compute the standard error of the mean of the values in each group

size()

Compute the number of values in each group

skew() *

Compute the skew of the values in each group

std()

Compute the standard deviation of the values in each group

sum()

Compute the sum of the values in each group

var()

Compute the variance of the values in each group

Build aggregation

we can define our functions from the built aggregation puzzles. Our function are build on object variables, so they have not any qoutation.

We can mix our functions with the built-in functions in pandas, what is a beauty!

In[19]:
from numpy._core.fromnumeric import mean
def mean_less_median(x):
  return x.mean() - x.median()

def range(x):
  return x.max() - x.min()

data[['bed', 'bath', 'price']].agg([mean_less_median, range, 'sum', 'median'])
Out[19]:
bed bath price
mean_less_median 3.321899e-01 4.842355e-01 4.024382e+05

sum 2.582867e+06 1.965234e+06 7.939894e+11
median 3.000000e+00 2.000000e+00 4.750000e+05

rank ( )

Ranking in pandas is line up the numbers from smallest to largest, and take number or place or position of each one.

The place is the rank.

# Generated example
s = pd.Series([100, 50, 50, 200])
s.rank()

# ranked numbers:
0    3.0
1    1.5
2    1.5
3    4.0
dtype: float64

So, the values were sorted: 50, 50, 100, 200

Ranking them: let's sort our data from the higest to lower and number them to make a ranking.

This is a entire list of column (price)

diff ( )

Diff function to compare values. Default period set to 1.

diff ( ) - subtracts data.

Tell you how much money changed.

We look at the change in the time, taking previous value comparing to next one. For example we take data from Tuesday and compering with Monday at the same week.

shift ( )

Shift method: moves data up and down in the time (or position) whthout changing the values themselves.

It does not calculate anything.

It only repositions data.

Sliding the column while keeping the numbers intact.

shift() does not calculate , it moves the numbers forward or backwards (usually for later comparison).

Take the EUR currency and lagging by one period (day)

rolling ( )

Rolling function : pandas creates window over time (past) and applies the function to this window interval. So, looks back to the rows in the back and applies window only to that window, Returns one value per row.

This is windowed calculation.

Returned size of series is the same, just NaNs (false) and true value for each window.

In[590]:
EUR_shifted['pct_change_5_avg'] = EUR_shifted['%change'].rolling(window=5).mean()

standardize the value:

We can create a function to standardize the values from the dataset. The function formula is below:

#

(value - mean() / std() )

We subtracted average from each value of series , and next divided by std deviation.

In[620]:
# z_score function

def standardize(x):
  z_score = (x - x.mean()) / x.std()
  return z_score
